Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

miscConds.notes:
Defendant will comply with all federal, and state laws, and local alcohol, drug and violence ordinances during the period of this Agreement.  If there is a case charging a violation of a criminal statute or local ordinance pending when this agreement is due to expire, this agreement continues in effect until 30 days after such case is revolved.  If the Defendant is charged with a criminal offense in a case subsequent to the Court's approval of this agreement, a finding of probable cause in that case is sufficient basis for termination of this agreement. 
Defendant will keep Douglas County Clerk of Courts informed of his address and telephone number at all times, and stipulates that the sending of notice by regular mail to the address on file with the Clerk of Courts constitutes sufficient notice of any court hearings scheduled in this matter.  The non-appearance of the defendant may result in the issuance of an arrest warrant. 
Defendant will continue to comply with all bail or bond conditions ordered by the Court while this agreement is in effect.

Defendant will complete the 27-week Men's Nonviolence Class at Domestic Abuse Intervention Program (DAIP) in Duluth, MN. Mandatory orientations are held once a month. Information is available at 218-722-2781 ext. 106 or at www.theduluthmodel.org. The defendant will provide proof of completion of the program to the DA's office within 30 days of completion of the program. Defendant will be truthful and accurate with the DAIP and will inform the program staff of the current charge and any domestic abuse charges in other pending or resolved cases. 
If Defendant makes a good faith effort to complete the program before the date above, but is not able to complete the program by that date, the date for completion of the program may be extended by agreement of the parties upon reasonable notice to the District Attorney's Office. Failure to notify the State of hardship in completing the program prior to the date agreed upon constitutes evidence that Defendant did not make a good faith effort to schedule and complete said program.
